original_description: Metric values contained in Pre-kindergarten School Quality Reports
autoddg_description: This dataset contains information about pre-kindergarten school quality, providing insights into various aspects of early childhood education. The dataset includes details such as site ID, program code, program name, and program type, as well as enrollment numbers, daily start times, and availability of meals and playspaces. Additionally, it includes scores and ratings for emotional support, classroom organization, and instructional support, as well as assessment metrics for ECERS (Early Childhood Environment Rating Scale). The dataset can be used to analyze and compare pre-K school quality across different locations, identify areas for improvement, and inform policy decisions.
llama_ufd_no_shot_descriptions: This dataset contains metric values from the 2016-2017 School Quality Reports (SQS) for Pre-Kindergarten (PK) programs in New York City. The data is collected by the New York City Department of Education (DOE) and provides information on various aspects of PK programs, including enrollment, program type, and quality metrics such as CLASS and ECERS scores. The dataset can be used to analyze and compare the quality of PK programs across different locations and to inform decisions about resource allocation and program improvement.
few_shot_Description: This dataset contains metric values from the 2016-2017 School Quality Reports (SQS) for Pre-Kindergarten (PK) programs in New York City, collected by the New York City Department of Education (DOE). The data provides information on various aspects of PK programs, including enrollment, program type, and quality metrics such as CLASS and ECERS scores. This dataset can be used to analyze and compare the quality of PK programs across different locations, inform decisions about resource allocation and program improvement, and answer questions about the effectiveness of PK programs in supporting children's learning and development. It can also be used to investigate the relationship between program characteristics and quality metrics, and to identify areas for improvement in PK programs.

original_description: Properties remediated under OER's oversight, both in the E-Designation program and the NYC Voluntary Cleanup Program. Includes sites completed and in progress.
autoddg_description: This dataset contains information about environmental cleanup sites in New York City, providing a comprehensive overview of projects, locations, and details. The dataset includes unique project numbers, project names, and street information, as well as spatial data such as latitude, longitude, and zip codes. The semantic profile reveals that the dataset contains spatial and temporal data, with columns representing locations, identifiers, and concepts. This dataset can be used to analyze and visualize environmental cleanup efforts, identify trends and patterns, and inform policy decisions. By leveraging this dataset, researchers and policymakers can better understand the scope and impact of environmental cleanup initiatives in New York City.
llama_ufd_no_shot_descriptions: This dataset, OER Cleanup Sites, contains information on properties remediated under the oversight of the Mayor's Office of Environmental Remediation (OER). The dataset includes sites that have been completed and are in progress, both in the E-Designation program and the NYC Voluntary Cleanup Program. This dataset can be used by researchers, policymakers, and community stakeholders to understand the scope and progress of environmental remediation efforts in New York City, identify areas of contamination, and inform decisions related to brownfield redevelopment and community revitalization.
few_shot_Description: This dataset, provided by the Mayor's Office of Environmental Remediation (OER), contains information on properties remediated under OER's oversight, including sites that have been completed and those that are in progress. The dataset includes project details such as project names, street addresses, boroughs, and zip codes, as well as information on the OER programs involved, such as the E-Designation program and the NYC Voluntary Cleanup Program. This dataset can be used to analyze the scope and impact of environmental remediation efforts in New York City, identify trends and patterns in cleanup activities, and inform policy decisions related to environmental protection and community development. The data may be useful for researchers, policymakers, and community stakeholders interested in understanding the effectiveness of OER's programs and the environmental benefits of remediation efforts.

original_description: Census Tracts from the 2010 US Census for New York City including portions under water. These boundary files are derived from the US Census Bureau's TIGER project and have been geographically modified to fit the New York City base map. All previously released versions of this data are available on the DCP Website: BYTES of the BIG APPLE. Current version: 25c
autoddg_description: This dataset contains spatial and temporal information about New York City, providing a comprehensive overview of the city's geography and demographics. The dataset includes columns such as the_geom, which contains spatial data in the form of coordinates, and ctlabel, which represents temporal entities with a resolution of numerical values. The semantic profile of the dataset reveals that it can be used for geospatial calculations, category labeling, and aggregation key purposes. This dataset can be used to analyze and understand the city's spatial and temporal patterns, making it a valuable resource for researchers and policymakers interested in New York City.
llama_ufd_no_shot_descriptions: This dataset contains the 2010 US Census Tract boundaries for New York City, including areas under water. The boundaries were derived from the US Census Bureau's TIGER project and have been modified to fit the New York City base map. The Department of City Planning (DCP) released this dataset, which is categorized under City Government. This dataset can be used to identify and analyze census tracts, neighborhoods, and community development areas within New York City. It can also be used to determine eligibility for Community Development Block Grants and to understand the demographics and characteristics of different areas within the city.
few_shot_Description: This dataset contains the 2010 Census Tracts for New York City, including areas under water, derived from the US Census Bureau's TIGER project and modified to fit the New York City base map. The dataset provides a comprehensive view of the city's census tracts, including their boundaries, identifiers, and attributes such as community development block grant eligibility and neighborhood tabulation area codes. This dataset can be used by researchers, policymakers, and urban planners to analyze population demographics, track changes in census tracts over time, and inform decisions about community development and resource allocation. The data is accurate and complete, with a total of 25c versions available on the DCP Website: BYTES of the BIG APPLE. However, users should note that the boundaries have been modified to fit the New York City base map, which may affect the accuracy of the data for certain applications.

autoddg_description: This dataset contains information on civil litigation cases, specifically focusing on the matter of Gamble Harold vs. Lawrence Cook ET AL. The dataset provides details on the court proceedings, including the court name, plaintiffs and defendants' firms, and the litigation start and closed dates. The data also includes financial information, such as total disposition amounts, city payouts, and expenses. With a unique matter name and court name, this dataset can be used to analyze and understand the characteristics of civil litigation cases in the Southern District of New York. The semantic profile reveals that the dataset contains spatial and temporal data, making it suitable for spatial and temporal analysis.
llama_ufd_no_shot_descriptions: This dataset contains case-related information about civil litigation, specifically from the Law Department (LAW) in the City Government category. It includes details about the matter name, court name, plaintiffs and defendants' firms, law department division, litigation start date, closed date, disposition, and financial information such as total disposition amount, city payout amount, and city received amount. This dataset can be used to analyze and understand the trends and patterns in civil litigation cases handled by the Law Department, and to gain insights into the city's financial obligations and payouts.
few_shot_Description: This dataset contains case-related information about civil litigation cases handled by the Law Department (LAW) of the City Government. The dataset includes details about the matter name, court name, plaintiffs' and defendants' firms, law department division assigned to the matter, litigation start date, closed date, disposition, and total disposition amount. With this dataset, researchers and analysts can gain insights into the city's financial obligations and payouts, as well as understand trends and patterns in civil litigation cases. The dataset provides a comprehensive view of the city's litigation landscape, including the types of cases filed, the parties involved, and the outcomes of the cases. The dataset is suitable for researchers, policymakers, and legal professionals who want to analyze and understand the city's litigation data.

original_description: Parking Permits issued for a particular purpose in designated parking zones or at specific locations for prearranged periods of time,and is not issued for commercial activities or to commercial vehicles.These permits are issued pursuant to Section 4-08 (o)(4) of Title 34 of the Rules of the City of New York.
autoddg_description: This dataset contains information on NYC parking permits, providing a comprehensive overview of permit details, including permit numbers, expiration dates, company names, and locations. The dataset spans a single unique value, covering a specific period from July 12, 2007, to September 3, 2007. The semantic profile reveals that the dataset is rich in spatial and temporal information, with columns representing locations, dates, and times. This dataset can be used to analyze parking permit trends, identify patterns in permit issuance and expiration, and explore the relationship between permit types and locations.
llama_ufd_no_shot_descriptions: This dataset, titled Single Use Parking Permit- On Street, contains information on parking permits issued by the Department of Transportation (DOT) for specific purposes and locations. The dataset includes details such as permit number, expiration date, company name, city, state, and zip code of the permit holder, as well as the issue date, permit print date, permit type, location, valid dates and times, and conditions of the permit. This dataset can be used by researchers, policymakers, and transportation planners to analyze parking permit issuance patterns, understand the needs of different communities, and inform decisions related to transportation infrastructure and urban planning. The dataset is particularly useful for studying temporary or special event parking permits, which are issued for a limited duration and are not intended for commercial activities or commercial vehicles.
few_shot_Description: This dataset contains information on Single Use Parking Permits issued by the Department of Transportation (DOT) in New York City. The dataset provides details on permits issued for specific purposes, such as loading and unloading equipment, and is particularly useful for analyzing parking permit issuance patterns, understanding the needs of different communities, and informing decisions related to transportation infrastructure and urban planning. The dataset includes information on permit issuance, including the permit number, expiration date, company name, location, valid dates and times, and conditions of the permit. This dataset can be used to study temporary or special event parking permits, which are issued for a limited duration and are subject to specific conditions and restrictions. The data can also be used to analyze the types of permits issued, the locations where they are permitted, and the reasons for which they are needed.
